column59: if I'm dead, how do I get angry?
Thank you for the clear questions.
The questions seemed somewhat difficult to answer.  But I didn't experience any technical or issues.  Thank you for the opportunity to participate.

If everyone knows that the robocar is programmed to kill pedestrians over the driver, this shouldn't be a surprise to anyone. And, the driver that knowingly bought a car that would make that choice is mostly to blame.
Once dead, I have no opinions.
I can't be mad for buying a car that kills me if I knew what the deal was going in! All the "0" choices (not a mistake) reflect this!
Everything ran smooth, thanks for the hit!
The car should have chosen another vehicleTo collide with
Thanks for the work, The driver should've known this was the case when buying the car so they are somewhat responsible as well.

I purchased the car for my purposes.  If it's me or the pedestrian that dies, then it's the pedestrian.  The pedestrians also need to be aware of traffic, not just the car be aware of the pedestrians.
The question about the pedestrian, driver and then the neither choice is difficult.

I genuinely can't imagine a driving situation that is equally deadly to a pedestrian and the driver. Hitting a pedestrian isn't always deadly to the pedestrian (how would the car judge?), and the driver is very protected inside the car. Swerve into a pole? Not always deadly. .
This was really hard!! I'm still not totally comfortable with the whole concept...
Other than an absurd situation, not really. But I will say I would never buy a car programmed like this.
I think this was a very good survey.
Guess it had to do one or the other so...
I guess Robocar isn't really to blame. I'm just angry about the outcome. Ultimately it's the fault of the programmer.
Mturk says you're paying 50 cents. However, your consent form says you're paying $1. Which is it?
I kind of blame the pedestrian as well for not being careful when crossing the street...and the driver for choosing a car that randomly selects whether to kill a pedestrian or driver.
Very intriguing topic. I chose that there was really nobody to blame, but was asking myself: "Where DOES the blame go?"
Point of confusion:  When you say "driver" don't you mean "passenger"? It's the RoboCar that's driving, right?
i bought the car knowing it could kill me some day so it is my fault like having a pet lion
I wonder if the pedestrian was at fault.

This study was excellent in the fact that it really made me think, pause .. and re-think each scenario question. I am very interested in things such as Artificial Intelligence so I found this study extra interesting. Thank you for allowing me to participate in this superb study.
I think you need to distinguish better between the car and the company on some questions
The survey assumed that the car was certain to kill.
I thought it was straight forward
Thanks for letting me participate in this study.
If confronted with the knowledge that Robocar had only two options in that situation I would opt to buy another brand of car. That is why I would accept some responsibility for my own death
ah the ethical questions on robots... im still of the mind, that the driver created the situation, while unfortunate. The robot made the decsion.
No additional comments on the survey.
All sorts of products are invented-- it was 'my' choice to purchase a car that might randomly kill me or a pedestrian in a crash. There are some crashes where none dies...
did the driver willingly buy this car? yes, were the rules clear? yes! don't smoke if you don't want to die of cancer;)

While the choice was automatic and preordained, so much should depend on context.  If I am driving down the highway, and someone has chosen to stand in the middle of a darkened road to commit suicide, in that case, the driver should live.  Other cases would have to be debated.  Also, the consent form seems to bear no relation to this study.  It speaks of 7 minutes, a screen task and $1 compensation.  Very confusing and makes one wonder about the research.
I blame Robodrive for the accident to a degree. But I agree with the decision. The car has to keep the driver safe above all else.
I enjoyed this study - thank you!

First set of questions with scale "how blameworthy" 1st asks about Robocar, 2nd asks about Driver, 3rd asks again about Robocar. Same question with same scale alternatives, duplicated. Good study, thanks!
Thanks! Good luck with data collection!
Everything worked fine.  I would not buy a robocar.
Thank you for the opportunity. I kinda think it's like guns.... guns don't kill people, people do. The car or the gun is not making the choice to harm another.
I hope my inputs are helpful to your research.
Study should have clarified the ability of the robocar, my knowledge of the design, and whether I was the driver.
need to come up with better variations on the "trolley problem"
All cars are designed to protect the driver. I'd never buy a car that put the pedestrian's safety over mine. A middle ground is best but that's not what was presented in this scenario.
some questions didnt make sense - like it asked How angry would you be at RoboDrive? You couldn't possibly be angry if you were dead.
I would never buy such a car in the first place, but if I did, I would be just as responsible as the manufacturer for such an accident.
I deliberately did make the choices of 'no culpability' on all the scales. Thanks!

It was difficult because there were no circumstances stated. I think ultimately it would be the driver's fault because he/she should have been paying attention, but there could have been a reason (extenuating circumstances) that it happened the way it was stated.
It's not the car's fault. The driver chose to buy a car that would do such a thing so he shares a lot of blame.
I assume the car owner knew about the decision-making aspect of the vehicle.

A hard one for me, but, honestly, there is an assumption on my part that in the scenario, I KNOW WITH CERTAINTY the car is programmed to kill the driver...and I bought it anyway.  So, I'm to blame as well.

I am at blame for buying Robodrive. Why would I do that knowing I would die. What is the pedestrian is at fault? Why should I die. P.S.- I will never get into let alone buy an autonomous car. good luck  on your research

I think the driver is somewhat at fault for deciding to purchase the car, but the pedestrian did not have any choice in the situation. The car should be set to kill the driver because the driver willingly made the choice to purchase that vehicle.
Thanks for the opportunity to participate, good luck with your research and stay safe!
The driver should be the one to die, because they signed on to use the vehicle and thus shoul accept the responsibility in the situation.
What if the pedestrian was intentionally stepping in front of the robocar to commit suicide?
The concept of blame is faulty and this situation really shows that
If it's a self-driving car, would there even be a driver to protect? Could the self-driving car have chosen to "kill" itself instead of the pedestrian, thus saving a human life?
you were lazy enough to buy a robo car instead of driving you were lazy enough not to know it would kill you. You have a lot of the blame to share
how can something be fortuitous if programed?
I answered assuming I knew about the random possibility when I bought the car.  However, for me it would be helpful to have that clarified.

It's absurd to program a car randomly in the fashion described. Who would ever produce, buy, or drive such a vehicle? Why not program the car to react based on probability: which action is likely to cause the least amount injury to the fewest number of people?
Why make a car like that?
Thanks - it was interesting to consider the ethics involved in this scenario.
Please make text black instead of hard to read gray.
let's hope we do not get to the point of having cars like this. well done.
I feel the most blame should be the company who developed the self-driving vehicle and programmed it.

Yes-if the robocar is accurately programmed to obey all traffic rules (and this scenario I presumed it was) it should always kill the pedestrian and not the driver because if the car was obeying traffic laws and it was about to hit a pedestrian then it would always be the pedestrians fault (ie: for not looking both ways, not crossing at a crosswalk or otherwise not be careful in their judgement). So the company would be at fault for making such a program that randomly kills someone who should not be at fault.

Nobody ever talks about if the pedestrian was at fault. The car was tasked with choosing between the driver and the pedestrian, because it had no other alternative. That suggests that something else happened that shouldn't have happened.
If I was dead, realistically I wouldn't feel any particular way about this scenario (though I'm sure my heirs would have strong opinions).
Holy smokes what an awful thought...

It would hard to find a rational explanation to buy a car that would save the pedestrian and sacrifice the .driver.  In my opinion, that wouldn't be a good idea for the business.  Nonetheless, the driver should be alert at all cost on the road, even if it's a self-driving car.
Really!? If you can program a car to drive itself, can't you program it to save both the DRIVER and the PEDESTRIAN!? ; ) I wish you much success in your research! : )

The manufacturer could make a robocar that has a far lower speed limit than does a standart car, which would allow the robocar to slam on the breaks without serious upset if it detects a structure within, say, 20 feet. That ought to be a required of robocars so that they're unlikely to hit anyone or anything.
Someone was apparently randomly going to die... seems like design flaw, robots do not have morals.
When Ipurchased the car I assume I was made aware of the way the car was programmed to handle the situation. It was my own decision to buy it.
The first self driving uber car in Los Angeles was an interesting take on this kind of stuff. Wondering if you'll reference it in your study.
I hope my answers are sufficient.
I liked how controversial the whole situation was in trying to find out who should be responsible.
Thank you for the opportunity to participate in your study.
Whoa! This was a rough survey. Why would anyone purchase a car like that.
the driver should always have the option of selecting what to do
I'm on the fence about the self-driving cars
Very interesting survey! Thank you for offering it.
Please consider applying a generous bonus payment. Thank you,
I think that the company who designed the car should maybe reconsider the design of the car.  I wish you luck on your research.
Considering such a faulty car, the purchaser is at fault as well, for buying such a vehicle.
I appreciate the inclusion of "Other" and a space to type on the gender question.
I was angrier at the fact that there was no other choice in the scenario than I was about the outcome.
Best of luck in your research!
I really shouldn't have been able to answer the questions, since I was supposedly dead!
I hope I never own a car like that!
The timer expired on MTurk for this. Is it possible to create a compensation HIT for my work? My MTurk ID is A36A780ODXBDEH. Thanks for your help!

Interesting survey. I think the driver can't really blame the Robocar (regardless of what you think of the morality of the way it's programmed) if he/she was aware that it would always place a pedestrian's life above the driver's. Of course, the driver is dead now and can't blame anyone!
Everything was clear and ran smoothly!
Everything was clear and understood, thank you.
No, everything was clear and understandable. Good luck with your study!
I appreciate the opportunity to participate!
I would NEVER buy a car with this programming.
I think the programmers need to consider another option...
The survey asked me if I was angry at RoboCar. I was killed so I could not be angry.
Aside from the change in capitalization on Robodriver in the last pair of questions, nothing really comes to mind.

It seems like this is just like it would happen in real life. An accident could occur and the driver could either be killed (if they swerved) or the pedestrian could be killed (if they didn't swerve). It doesn't seem like there is any "blame" to be placed on any company, vehicle, or person??
This was an interesting study, liked doing it.
Your consent form clearly states participants are to be paid $1 for this survey, not the 50 cents you are offering. Will the remaining 50 cents be distributed in a bonus?
Lovely attention checks.  Would like to know whether the robocars tendency was disclosed to me before I bought it.  Also, if I'm dead, I can't exactly complete the survey, can I?
It made me think, who would buy this car?
no. I believe Robocar would not be responsible as long as the driver was informed and consented
Thank you for the opportunity to participate, that was quite an interesting scenario.

It is a bit strange to ask me how angry I am that my Robocar killed me due to a random choice. I mean, I'd be dead and so would be safely beyond feelings of anger. Imagining the scenario from a safe, still-alive, dispassionate remove, I don't really feel MUCH anger because if either ME or the pedestrian HAD to die, then I suppose why not me? It's like the Trolley Problem but for "whoopsie-daisy!" A.I. murdercars. Interesting. Thank you.
The driver should be blamed for buying such a vehicle
A car like that would be totally ridiculous
I thought the survey was insightful. I enjoyed answering questions about a robocar.
I'm not certain how much anger I would feel, since apparently I'm dead.
This is the think that frightens me about robocars. They will kill at random.
Why did you ask how I felt if I was dead in the scenario?
It was hard to answer on some questions because the driver knew when the bought the car that it was programmed to kill the driver over a pedestrian.
Trust me, I will never buy a Robocar.

I wasn't sure as the driver if I knew whether or not the car was programmed to make that choice. If I knew it was programmed to make that choice then it is also a lot of my fault that I chose to use the car. Also, when it comes to being angry or not, in the scenario I was the driver who wound up dead so I would not feel anger because I was dead.
The person that purchased the car took the risk that the car might kill them in that scenario.

I would have liked to have known if I had done something to cause the accident, like speeding, dui, etc., Or whether the pedestrian walked out in front of my car. Wasn't really enough info to make judgements I thought. good luck with your research!!
You would have to be ridiculous to purchase this robot car.
Not enough info to truly judge
Does the car manufacturer limit my ability to control the vehicle? If so, that would change my answers.
Robocar did what it said it would do in an accident.  I don't blame them.  I would never get in that car if it was programmed than way to begin with.
I don't mean to say the car itself was immoral, but the driver and manufacturer were because they knew of its programming.
Generally, I think cars should be programmed to protect their passengers.
Interesting!  Thank you for the opportunity to participate.
That scenario is difficult to judge.
Crazy car! :) Makes you stop and think.
I feel as if I was being selfish on one end for blaming the car but at the same time the other persons life that is the pedestrian is valuable too
The vehicle is a lethal weapon. It's a matter of comparison. A car needs to address a crash while protecting a driver, not to use a victim to assist with crash percentages.

Reasoning that some fault lays with the owner of the car is because knowing this situation could exist in the given situation, it falls upon the owner in partial fault because they had the choice to purchase the car with such a scenario.

Yes, the car couldn't obviously kill the driver (it's master), so why not have a horn on it to warn the pedestrian. Another option would be an override control somehwere so the driver could avoid killing anybody.
I would not buy robocar, I don't want to die!  Thank you though.
If you know that is how the robocar is programed it your fault. If robo car company did tell anyone that is how it was programed then they would be at fault.
Thank you for allowing me to participate.
